You can read the body of an http.Request to a string in Golang by using the ioutil.ReadAll() function from the ioutil package. Here's an example code snippet:

```go
package main

import (
	"fmt"
	"io/ioutil"
	"net/http"
)

func handler(w http.ResponseWriter, r *http.Request) {
	body, err := ioutil.ReadAll(r.Body)
	if err != nil {
		http.Error(w, "Error reading request body", http.StatusInternalServerError)
		return
	}

	fmt.Fprintf(w, "Body: %s", body)
}

func main() {
	http.HandleFunc("/", handler)
	http.ListenAndServe(":8080", nil)
}
```

Goroutines are lightweight threads managed by the Go runtime. They allow concurrent execution of functions or methods. Goroutines are more efficient than traditional threads because they have a smaller memory footprint and the Go runtime can multiplex a large number of goroutines onto a smaller number of OS threads.

Here's a practical example showcasing the usage of goroutines in Golang:

```go
package main

import (
	"fmt"
	"time"
)

func printNumbers() {
	for i := 1; i <= 5; i++ {
		fmt.Println(i)
		time.Sleep(1 * time.Second)
	}
}

func main() {
	go printNumbers() // Start a new goroutine to execute printNumbers concurrently

	for i := 1; i <= 5; i++ {
		fmt.Println("Main goroutine:", i)
		time.Sleep(1 * time.Second)
	}

	time.Sleep(6 * time.Second) // Wait for goroutines to finish before exiting
}
```

Channels in Golang are a way for goroutines to communicate and synchronize their execution. They provide a means for one goroutine to send data to another goroutine. Channels are typed, meaning they can only transfer values of a specific data type.

To create a channel, you use the make() function with the channel type specified. Channels can be created with or without a buffer. Channels without a buffer are synchronous, meaning the sender will block until the receiver is ready to receive the data. Channels with a buffer allow a certain number of elements to be stored in the channel without blocking the sender.

Here's an example showcasing sending and receiving values via channels:

```go
package main

import "fmt"

func sender(ch chan int) {
	for i := 1; i <= 5; i++ {
		ch <- i // Send value i to the channel
	}
	close(ch) // Close the channel after sending all values
}

func main() {
	ch := make(chan int) // Create an unbuffered channel

	go sender(ch) // Start a goroutine to send values to the channel

	// Receive values from the channel
	for num := range ch {
		fmt.Println("Received:", num)
	}
}
```

In this example, the `sender` function sends values 1 to 5 to the channel `ch`. The `main` function creates the channel, starts a goroutine to send values, and then receives and prints the values received from the channel using a `for range` loop.

Remember to close the channel after sending all values to avoid deadlocks. Use the `close()` function to close the channel.

Channels are a powerful feature in Go for managing communication between goroutines and are essential for building concurrent applications.

